definition.value: Z-discs (Z-disk, Z-line, Z-band) delineate the lateral borders of sarcomeres and are the smallest functional units in striated muscle. The core of a Z-disc consists of actin filaments coming from adjacent sarcomeres which are crosslinked by alpha-actinin molecules. Z-discs, which are difficult to detect in conventional light microscopy, appear in the longitudinal view of electron microscopy as electron dense bands with varying sizes, ranging from 30 to 50 nm in fast muscle and 100 t0 140 nm in slow muscle and cardiac myocytes.

definition.value: The dermal sinus tracks in from the skin and may end in the soft tissues, epidural space, or intradurally, where it is commonly associated with (generally benign) intradural inclusion tumors (including dermoid, epidermoid, or teratoma), thickened fatty filum, tethered cord, or diastematomyelia (split cord syndrome). Dermal sinus tracts are different from innocuous coccygeal dimples, which are located lower within the gluteal cleft and are not associated with cutaneous stigmata; completely 'classic' dimples do not require further workup or follow-up. See Figure 1 of PMID:31484633.

Any abnormal phenotypic feature observed in a biospecimen derived from a lymph node, generally obtained by lymph node biopsy (removal of lymph node tissue for microscopic examination).

definition.value: The lymph nodes are organized lymphoid organs that contain lymphocytes within a fine reticular stroma. The structures within a lymph node include the capsule, subcapsular sinus, cortex (B cell zone with follicles and germinal centers), paracortex (T cell zone), medullary sinuses, medullary cords and hilus.

value.value: Arquitectura anormal del tejido de los ganglios linfáticos

definition.value: Any phenotypic abnormality of the architecture of the tissue of a lymph node.

Each tissue is composed of many different cell types that assemble into organized patterns. Tissue architecture is defined by the cellular and extracellular compartments that cooperate with each other through division of labor.

definition.value: Any phenotypic abnormality within cells located in a lymph node.

value.value: Arquitectura alterada del tejido de los ganglios linfáticos

definition.value: An alteration that affects multiple components of the architecture of a lymph node.

Effacement of architecture typically refers to a cellular infiltrate destroying the normal follicular architecture of a lymph node. This effacement may result in sheets of cells that do not form clear architecture (seen in many lymphomas) or may lead to replacement of the normal architecture by atypical architecture, for example effacement of normal lymph node architecture (including normal follicles and patent lymph node sinuses) by many abnormal follicles in follicular lymphoma.

value.value: Arquitectura vagamente nodular de los ganglios linfáticos

definition.value: In contrast to normal lymph node architecture or that of follicular lymphoma, where follicles are typically distinct and readily identifiable on H&E stained biopsy sections, the cells within an atypical lymph node may show what appear to groups of cells forming vague nodules but not forming clear follicles.
This finding, if not an artifact of poor tissue processing, favors lymphoma but may be seen in reactive states.

value.value: Invasión capsular por linfocitos de los ganglios linfáticos

definition.value: Migration of substantial numbers of lymphocytes into the capsule of a lymph node.
Lymph node capsules are formed by fibrous tissue encapsulating the lymph node, and typically have few or no lymphocytes within the capsule itself.

definition.value: Migration of lymphocytes into the soft tissues surrounding the lymph node.

Lymph node capsules are formed by fibrous tissue encapsulating the lymph node, and typically the lymphocytes within a lymph node do not extravasate outside of the capsule into soft tissues surrounding the lymph node.

label.value: Scattered lymph node individual epithelioid histiocytes

definition.value: Many individual (not clustered) epithelioid histiocytes throughout at least part of a lymph node.

Histiocytes are tissue-resident macrophages with a moderate amount of cytoplasm that can occasionally show more abundant cytoplasm and appear similar to epithelial cells. These epithelioid histiocytes may be scattered and/or clustered together within lymph nodes under certain conditions, but are generally not prominent in benign non-reactive lymph nodes.

Histiocytes are tissue-resident macrophages with a moderate amount of cytoplasm that can occasionally show more abundant cytoplasm and appear similar to epithelial cells. These epithelioid histiocytes may be scattered and/or clustered together within lymph nodes under certain conditions, but are generally not prominent in benign non-reactive lymph nodes.

definition.value: A lymph node follicle is a loosely arranged structure with an outer mantle of small T lymphocytes and a germinal center composed of B lymphocytes, follicular dendritic cells, and macrophages.

value.value: Colonización de folículos por células de linfoma

label.value: Colonization of follicles by lymphoma cells

definition.value: In contrast to follicular lymphoma, which typically is a lymphoma that forms follicles or potentially completely replaces normal follicles, some lymphomas (most commonly marginal zone lymphoma) can infiltrate normal follicles so both normal lymphocytes and the infiltrating lymphoma cells are present. This is called colonization of follicles by the lymphoma cells.
Reduction in the average distance between adjacent lymph node follicles.

Follicles in lymph nodes are usually spaced apart, however in certain conditions such as florid reactive follicular hyperplasia and follicular lymphoma, the follicles can become very crowded, even back-to-back with few interfollicular cells in between.

value.value: Lisis folicular de los ganglios linfáticos

An abnormal morphology of hyperplastic lymph node follicles characterized by distortion of the follicular architecture by tongues and clusters of dark blue mantle cells impinging on and invading the reactive germinal center (Mostly T cells and mantle-zone B cells).
Centros germinales de ganglios linfáticos no polarizados

definition.value: A loss of the typical polarization of the architecture of a lymph node germinal center.

Germinal centers typically have one side containing mostly larger centroblasts and the other side containing mostly small centrocytes. The side with more centroblasts appears darker on an H&E stained section and is termed the dark zone and the other side appears lighter and is termed the light zone. This polarization of germinal center topology is often visualized on H&E stained sections of reactive lymph nodes but may not be as obvious if the germinal centers are small or if the specific section happens to contain mostly dark zone or mostly light zone. This polarization is typically lost in follicular lymphomas.

label.value: Irregularly shaped lymph node germinal centers

definition.value: A deviation from the typically fairly round or oval form of a lymph node germinal center.
Germinal centers may become more elongated and/or take on irregular shapes such as somewhat snake-like/serpentine or other shapes.
